Jeremy,

There will always be a market for less educated people and some to 
take advantage of that.  There is a a saying out there---- &quot;Stupid 
people don&#39;t know they&#39;re stupid&quot;.  How true is that.

-Steve 



--- In EVP-ITC@yahoogroups.com, Early Cuyler &lt;ecuyler@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Margaret, I can&#39;t argue with what you&#39;ve said.  I&#39;m just saying 
there are those who take advantage and should have no business in 
doing so.  One example I can give is Chris Moon.  He charges people 
to do box sessions.  I can&#39;t remember the exact fee, but it&#39;s 
outrageous that he&#39;s doing this, not to mention, he does so with a 
Frank&#39;s box.  He is a self proclaimed medium and I&#39;ve heard from many 
sources that he is nothing but a fake.  
&gt; 
&gt; So I attribute my frustration with people of this type, but again I 
say, as long as there are people dumb enough to pay for this, then 
there will always be those who take advantage.
&gt; 
&gt; Personally, I feel anyone who is gifted with mediumship or other 
advanced intuitive abilities should use it as a gift to help others, 
not for monetary gain.  I&#39;m not being judgmental here, that&#39;s just 
how I feel.  I have a friend who is also a legitimate medium and I 
don&#39;t agree that she should use her abilities for gain, but it 
doesn&#39;t mean I like her any less.  My not liking it won&#39;t change the 
fact that it happens, it&#39;s just the way  things go.   
&gt; 
&gt; Do I think that Ron is taking advantage of people?  No I don&#39;t.  
Ron says he uses the best parts available and that the cost of the 
Minibox is very close to what it costs to manufacture it.  How close, 
I have no idea.  On the other hand, I don&#39;t own one as I think $399 
or $449 for the &quot;crystal enhanced version,&quot; is a lot to pay for a 
device that, from what I&#39;ve heard, produces the same results as a 
Radio Shack radio for $25-$40.  
&gt; 
&gt; Jeremy
